body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

For loaders doing APM, code coverage, and other analysis tasks, it can be important to get the physical contents or location of the file being loaded. However, it's inefficient to read the file multiple times unnecessarily.

Say we need to do something with the resolved imported URL and the source that was loaded.

```js
export const load = async (url, context, nextLoad) => {
  // get the file contents, even though node will do it again anyway
  const source = readFile(fileURLToPath(url))
  record(url, source)
  return nextLoad(url, context)
}
```

When you're the only loader in the stack, you can let Node be the only one to read the file, by using its result:

```js
export const load = async (url, context, nextLoad) => {
  // let node do the actual load from disk, since it has to do it anyway
  const result = nextLoad(url, context)
  if (result.source) {
    record(url, result.source)
  }
  return result
}
```

This also would allow for processing source that came from some other location, such as an HTTP loader.

However, that _doesn't_ if your loader is executed after something that does transpilation, because then you get the transpiled source instead of the original source.

```console
$ node --loader=ts-node/esm --loader=my-loader foo.ts  # works, gets the typescript
$ node --loader=my-loader --loader=ts-node/esm foo.ts # gets the transpiled js!
```

So, I'm stuck reading the file that Node.js already read just a moment ago, which works, but is inefficient, and limited.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

This is a very straw proposal, I'm not attached to it at all. Probably it's actually bad, and we can come up with something much better. But something to achieve this goal would be pretty awesome.

Add `originalSource` to the context object returned by `nextLoad()` and `originalURL` to the object returned by `nextResolve`. This is the _first_ value that was set in the loader stack.

That means, it's either the result of the `defaultLoad`/`defaultResolve`, or the loader hook that returned a `{ shortCircuit: true }` result.

That also means that if you had an http loader that calls `fetch()` and then returns `{shortCircuit: true, source}`, or pulls code from a database, or generates it synthetically, etc, I'd be able to track coverage for that as well.

```js
export const load = async (url, context, nextLoad) => {
  // let node do the actual load from disk, since it has to do it anyway
  const result = nextLoad(url, context)
  if (result.originalSource) {
    record(url, result.originalSource)
  }
  return result
}
```

Of course, this will only work if the loaders in question are well behaved and efficiently created. If ts-node/esm in this example were to read the file itself and return a `shortCircuit:true` result rather than transpiling the results of `nextLoad`, then we're all stuck doing repeated work.

### What alternatives have you considered?

See above. Just reading file from disk a second time, and only handling cases where it's a `file://` url rather than something else.

