Title: test_runner: non-file-based parallel tests

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

[jsdom](https://github.com/jsdom/) has lots of tests. Most of our tests are from the web platform tests suite. What this means is that we have (via a submodule) thousands of `.html` files, each of which correspond to a test case.

To run these tests currently, using mocha, we perform the equivalent of the following code:

```js
const allTestsToRun = gatherTests();

describe("Web platform tests", () => {
  for (const toRun of allTestsToRun) {
    test(toRun, async () => {
      const jsdom = await JSDOM.fromFile(toRun);
      reportResultsUsing(jsdom);
    });
  }
});
```

([actual code here](https://github.com/jsdom/jsdom/blob/main/test/web-platform-tests/run-wpts.js), [simpler special-case version here](https://github.com/jsdom/jsdom/blob/main/test/web-platform-tests/run-tuwpts.js), [inner test function here](https://github.com/jsdom/jsdom/blob/main/test/web-platform-tests/run-single-wpt.js).)

I was thinking, can I get these tests to run in parallel? Maybe using the node Node.js test runner that I've been upgrading my other projects to?

It seems like the answer is no. The Node.js test runner's notion of parallelism is file-based. So there's no way to run the various inner `test()` functions in my loop above, each in their own thread.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

I can understand why running functions in their own thread is annoying. In my example above, I am closing over the `toRun` variable, so we'd need some way of indicating that and serializing it.

One possible API for this would be the following:

```js
const { run } = require("node:test");

run({
  concurrency: true,
  inputData: allTestsToRun,
  testFileCreator: (toRun) => {
    return `
const test = require("node:test");

test("${toRun}",  async () => {
  const jsdom = await JSDOM.fromFile("${toRun}");
  reportResultsUsing(jsdom);
});
`;
  }
})
  .compose(tap)
  .pipe(process.stdout);
```

i.e. something which lets me dynamically create test files. https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/49606 seems somewhat related.

Or, you could do something with (serializable) test functions directly, where behind the scenes you `toString()` the function.

Or, you could have some sort of parameterization ability to pass to the test files, e.g.

```js
const { run } = require("node:test");

run({
  concurrency: true,
  variants: allTestsToRun,
  files: [path.resolve("./run-wpt-test.js")]
})
  .compose(tap)
  .pipe(process.stdout);
```

```js
// run-wpt-test.js:
const test = require("node:test");
const toRun = require("node:test").currentVariant; // or import.meta or something I guess

test(toRun, async () => {
  const jsdom = await JSDOM.fromFile(toRun);
  reportResultsUsing(jsdom);
});
```

In none of these ideas do I get the nice grouping of all the WPTs under one `describe()`, but that isn't so important anyway.

### What alternatives have you considered?

Mocha, our current test runner, seems to use a similar file-based strategy as far as I can tell, so it doesn't work.

We could write out thousands of stub .js files as a pre-test step, and then use them to construct the `run()` call. It's possible this would save us some time overall, since that file I/O could itself be parallelized. But it feels very silly.

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

`unhandledRejection` provides the rejected promise to the listener, but `uncaughtExceptionMonitor` doesn't provide anything when the origin is `unhandledRejection`.

By providing the rejected promise, one could get more insight into unhandled promises without attaching a listener to the `unhandledRejection` event.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

Add the rejected promise as a third parameter to the listener of a `uncaughtExceptionMonitor` event.

```
process.on('uncaughtExceptionMonitor', (err, origin, details) => {
  if (origin === 'unhandledRejection') {
    // details is the rejected promise.
  } else {
    // details is something else, or undefined.
  }
});
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

