body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

It is currently not straightforward to know if an `uncaughtException` originated from an `EventEmitter` that emitted an `error` event without any attached listener or from somewhere else. Making the distinction and providing the emitter itself in a similar fashion to providing the rejected promise in `unhandledRejection` events would help with debugging.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

A new origin for both `uncaughtException` and `uncaughtExceptionMonitor` events:

- `uncaughtException`
- `unhandledRejection`
- `unhandledErrorEvent` (name can be discussed)

Similar to https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/51201, we could have

```
process.on('uncaughtExceptionMonitor', (err, origin, details) => {
  if (origin === 'unhandledRejection') {
    // details is the rejected promise.
  } else if (origin === 'unhandledErrorEvent') {
    // details is the EventEmitter that emitted an `error` event.
  } else {
    // details is something else or undefined.
  }
});
```

Having the stack trace of the creation of the EventEmitter would be helpful in debugging as well but expensive as my understanding of https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/39917

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

text:
Title: Feature request: uncaughtExceptionMonitor to differentiate if the origin is an EventEmitter

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

It is currently not straightforward to know if an `uncaughtException` originated from an `EventEmitter` that emitted an `error` event without any attached listener or from somewhere else. Making the distinction and providing the emitter itself in a similar fashion to providing the rejected promise in `unhandledRejection` events would help with debugging.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

A new origin for both `uncaughtException` and `uncaughtExceptionMonitor` events:

- `uncaughtException`
- `unhandledRejection`
- `unhandledErrorEvent` (name can be discussed)

Similar to https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/51201, we could have

```
process.on('uncaughtExceptionMonitor', (err, origin, details) => {
  if (origin === 'unhandledRejection') {
    // details is the rejected promise.
  } else if (origin === 'unhandledErrorEvent') {
    // details is the EventEmitter that emitted an `error` event.
  } else {
    // details is something else or undefined.
  }
});
```

Having the stack trace of the creation of the EventEmitter would be helpful in debugging as well but expensive as my understanding of https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/39917

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Getting the platform (and displaying it in a way everyone understands) is a hassle in websites and other projects

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

it will make it easier for developers using node to get the current `platform` in a way that everyone understands

so instead of `win32` it will just directly be `windows`

here is a small map of it
```JSON
{
  "win32": "windows",
  "darwin": "macOS"
}
 ```

well thats it but judging how these are the 2 most popular OSes it is helpful

this would make cleaner code so instead of
```JavaScript
let OS;

if(platform() == 'win32') {
  OS = 'windows'
} else if(platform() == 'darwin') {
  OS = 'macOS'
} else {
  OS = platform()
)
// or
let OS  = platform() == 'win32' ? 'windows' : platform() == 'darwin' ? 'macOS' : platform()
```

it would just be
```JavaScript
let OS = platformSimple()
```

> Note: you may also add a process.platformSimple

### What alternatives have you considered?

While this may break some old code, maybe `process.platform` and `platform()` should be the simple on by default,
and if someone needs the the regular one the would use `platformDetailed()` or `process.platformDetailed`

