body:
### Version

v18.16.0 and up, v19.8.0 and up, v20.x, v21.x

### Platform

Darwin x86_64

### Subsystem

fs, stream

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

```js
const fs = require('fs');

const w = fs.createWriteStream('file.txt');

w.on('open', () => {
  w.write('hello');

  process.nextTick(() => {
    w.write('world');
    w.end();
  });
});

w.on('close', () => {
  console.log(fs.readFileSync('file.txt', 'utf8'));
});
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

Always

### What is the expected behavior? Why is that the expected behavior?

```helloworld```

### What do you see instead?

```worldhello```

### Additional information

The issue was caused by this change: https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/46818, which landed in node `v18.16.0` and `v19.8.0`.
(Thanks to @Fadorico for tracking down this change. I have also confirmed this by building node locally.)

This is causing the ['unzipper' module](https://github.com/ZJONSSON/node-unzipper/issues/286) to create corrupted files, because its ['fstream' dependency](https://github.com/npm/fstream/blob/bffea43c6a201c76bc85842539e09a779508790b/lib/file-writer.js#L38-L44) uses `fs.createWriteStream()` like in the example above.

It looks like when the stream's "open" event fires, the stream does not yet have the "constructed" flag set, so that might be why things are getting weird.

As a workaround, if I wait an additional tick after the "open" event, there are no issues:
```js
w.on('open', () => {
  process.nextTick(() => {
    w.write('hello');

    process.nextTick(() => {
      w.write('world');
      w.end();
    });
  });
});
```

text:
Title: fs.createWriteStream can cause out-of-order writes, in v18.16+

Body:
### Version

v18.16.0 and up, v19.8.0 and up, v20.x, v21.x

### Platform

Darwin x86_64

### Subsystem

fs, stream

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

```js
const fs = require('fs');

const w = fs.createWriteStream('file.txt');

w.on('open', () => {
  w.write('hello');

  process.nextTick(() => {
    w.write('world');
    w.end();
  });
});

w.on('close', () => {
  console.log(fs.readFileSync('file.txt', 'utf8'));
});
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

Always

### What is the expected behavior? Why is that the expected behavior?

```helloworld```

### What do you see instead?

```worldhello```

### Additional information

The issue was caused by this change: https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/46818, which landed in node `v18.16.0` and `v19.8.0`.
(Thanks to @Fadorico for tracking down this change. I have also confirmed this by building node locally.)

This is causing the ['unzipper' module](https://github.com/ZJONSSON/node-unzipper/issues/286) to create corrupted files, because its ['fstream' dependency](https://github.com/npm/fstream/blob/bffea43c6a201c76bc85842539e09a779508790b/lib/file-writer.js#L38-L44) uses `fs.createWriteStream()` like in the example above.

It looks like when the stream's "open" event fires, the stream does not yet have the "constructed" flag set, so that might be why things are getting weird.

As a workaround, if I wait an additional tick after the "open" event, there are no issues:
```js
w.on('open', () => {
  process.nextTick(() => {
    w.write('hello');

    process.nextTick(() => {
      w.write('world');
      w.end();
    });
  });
});
```

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

The `throws` assertion (and its relatives) allows matching a string property using a regex, but there are two shortcomings with this interface:

1. It works for strings only.
2. Even regexes have limitations.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

If the expected object provides a callable as the corresponding property value, this must be a boolean-valued matcher which simply takes the actual value as the sole parameter.
```typescript
const error = Object.assign(
    new TypeError("Wrong value"),
    {code: 123}
);

assert.throws(() => throw error, {
    message: "Wrong value",
    code: value => value >= 100
});
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

An alternative proposal is that the `number` type specifically is made to work with regex comparison, too. But this leaves other types such as `Date` without an obvious solution.

A workaround is to extract the problematic properties before the main assertion, making assertions on them either immediately (as in the following example) or later:
```typescript
const error = Object.assign(
    new TypeError("Wrong value"),
    {code: 123}
);

assert.throws(
    () => {
        assert.ok(error.value >= 100);
        throw error;
    },
    {message: "Wrong value"}
);
```
The benefit in supporting a custom tester function is that we're able to keep the assertions together regardless of the property value type.

