body:
### Version

22.9.0, 20.18.0

### Platform

```text
Darwin Kernel Version 24.0.0: Tue Sep 24 23:39:07 PDT 2024; root:xnu-11215.1.12~1/RELEASE_ARM64_T6000 arm64

Linux 4.18.0-553.16.1.el8_10.x86_64 #1 SMP Thu Aug 1 04:16:12 EDT 2024 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux
```


### Subsystem

_No response_

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

**Note**: I know the example code is technically incorrect, however, this pattern is a trimmed down example of some code that made it into production. We'll be catching this going forward using [no-await-in-promise-methods](https://github.com/sindresorhus/eslint-plugin-unicorn/blob/main/docs/rules/no-await-in-promise-methods.md). Even though it's incorrect I wouldn't have expected this to crash the process


Create a JS file with the following content and run it

```js
async function pThrow() {
  await Promise.resolve();
  throw new Error("Hello");
}

async function pResolve() {
  await Promise.resolve();
}
async function main() {
  try {
    await Promise.all([pResolve(), pThrow(), await pThrow()]);
  } catch (e) {
    console.error("Caught in main try/catch", e);
  }
}
main().catch((e) => {
  console.error("Caught on main function");
});
```

The output is:
```
Caught in main try/catch Error: Hello
    at pThrow (/Users/tom/dev/test/promise.js:3:9)
    at async main (/Users/tom/dev/test/promise.js:11:46)
/Users/tkolanko/dev/test/promise.js:3
  throw new Error("Hello");
        ^

Error: Hello
    at pThrow (/Users/tom/dev/test/promise.js:3:9)

Node.js v22.9.0
```

I noticed a few interesting things:
1. Change the `await pThrow()` to `pThrow()` and the problem is not reproducible, ex:  `await Promise.all([pResolve(), pThrow(), pThrow()]);`
2. Change the first `pThrow()` to `pResolve()` and the problem is not reproducible, ex: `await Promise.all([pResolve(), pResolve(), await pThrow()]);`

This crash only occurs when you have both a rejected promise and a rejection on an awaited promise inside of Promise.all


### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

every time

### What is the expected behavior? Why is that the expected behavior?

The catch handler that wraps the promise.all is able to capture the rejection

### What do you see instead?

NodeJS crashes

### Additional information

_No response_

