body:
### Affected URL(s)

https://nodejs.org/en/learn/test-runner/mocking

### Description of the problem

The example given  "[Modules + units](https://nodejs.org/en/learn/test-runner/mocking#modules--units)" uses a call to mock.fn() without any parameters, causing " barMock.mockImplementationOnce" to fail later on.

I am not sure if the example is only for demonstration purposes but I tried to run it :)

` const barMock = mock.fn();`

Later on it calls:
```
 barMock.mockImplementationOnce(function bar_mock() {
      /* … */
    });
```
Since the barMock function did not receive a function parameter above, the call to barMock.mockImplementationOnce fails.

### What is the problem this feature will solve?

I often find myself wanting to make a temporary directory for use during execution of a single function, for example because I'm going to `execSync` some process which creates temporary files in the current directory. `mkdtemp` works great to create the thing, but then I have to wrap in in a `try`/`finally` to handle cleanup.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

This seems like a good case for the [fancy new `using` syntax](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-explicit-resource-management). It would have to return an object with a `[Symbol.dispose]` and a `path` property instead of just a string, but then instead of 

```js
let tempDir;
try {
  tempDir = fs.mkdtempSync(path.join(os.tmpdir(), 'prefix-'));
  spawnSync(command, [], { cwd: tempDir });
  // etc
} finally {
  fs.rmSync(tempDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
}
```
we could have
```js
using tempDir = fs.mkdtempSync(path.join(os.tmpdir(), 'prefix-'), { disposable: true }); // or whatever
spawnSync(command, [], { cwd: tempDir.path });
// cleanup handled automatically
```

Compare [Python's `tempfile` module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html), which you can use as a context manager for the same sort of behavior:
```py
# create a temporary directory using the context manager
with tempfile.TemporaryDirectory() as tmpdirname:
    print('created temporary directory', tmpdirname)
# directory and contents have been removed
```

For bonus points it would be nice if this got cleaned up on process exit, but that's more work and it seems fine to just leave "might not get cleaned up if the process exits in the middle of your function" as a documented behavior.

### What alternatives have you considered?

We can of course just keep using `try`/`finally`, or not cleaning up.

text:
Title: disposable temporary directory

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

I often find myself wanting to make a temporary directory for use during execution of a single function, for example because I'm going to `execSync` some process which creates temporary files in the current directory. `mkdtemp` works great to create the thing, but then I have to wrap in in a `try`/`finally` to handle cleanup.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

This seems like a good case for the [fancy new `using` syntax](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-explicit-resource-management). It would have to return an object with a `[Symbol.dispose]` and a `path` property instead of just a string, but then instead of 

```js
let tempDir;
try {
  tempDir = fs.mkdtempSync(path.join(os.tmpdir(), 'prefix-'));
  spawnSync(command, [], { cwd: tempDir });
  // etc
} finally {
  fs.rmSync(tempDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
}
```
we could have
```js
using tempDir = fs.mkdtempSync(path.join(os.tmpdir(), 'prefix-'), { disposable: true }); // or whatever
