body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Nodejs 20.15.1 (somewhere around that version) and above can synchronously require ESM code now which makes it practical for CJS consumers to use ESM code.

I currently build my library to support both cjs and esm however I would rather consumers use ESM if they can. Currently, to force CJS projects to load ESM _if they can_, I need an extra shim;

```yaml
dist/index.mjs:
  console.log('esm')

dist/index.cjs:
  console.log('cjs')

dist/index.js:
  // CJS shim to force ESM
  try { 
    // Node > v20.15.1
    module.exports = require('./index.mjs') 
  } catch (_e) { 
    // Node <= v20.15.1
    module.exports = require('./index.cjs')
  }

dist/package.json:
  { "type": "commonjs" }

package.json:
  { 
     "type": "module" 
     "main": "./dist/index.cjs",
     "exports": {
        "import": "./dist/index.mjs",
        "require": "./dist/index.js",
        "default": "./dist/index.js"
     }
  }
```

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

One solution is to have versions of Node above the version that can synchronously load ESM select `import` rather than `require`.

Another option is to allow specifying the version of Node.js in the `exports` key and backporting that to the first version of Node that can support `require`ing ESM 

```json
{
  "exports": {
    "import": "./dist/index.mjs",
    "node >20.15.1": "./dist/index.mjs",
    "require": "./dist/index.js",
    "default": "./dist/index.js"
  }
}
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

