Title: Missing `Resolver` instantiation in `node:stream` docs

Body:
### Affected URL(s)

https://nodejs.org/api/stream.html#readabletoarrayoptions

### Description of the problem
Running the below code yields the error `ReferenceError: resolver is not defined`. 
```js
import { Readable } from 'node:stream';
import { Resolver } from 'node:dns/promises';

await Readable.from([1, 2, 3, 4]).toArray(); // [1, 2, 3, 4]

// Make dns queries concurrently using .map and collect
// the results into an array using toArray
const dnsResults = await Readable.from([
  'nodejs.org',
  'openjsf.org',
  'www.linuxfoundation.org',
]).map(async (domain) => {
  const { address } = await resolver.resolve4(domain, { ttl: true });
  return address;
}, { concurrency: 2 }).toArray();
```

I suggest instantiating the Resolver object first. For example:
```js
import { Readable } from 'node:stream';
import { Resolver } from 'node:dns/promises';

await Readable.from([1, 2, 3, 4]).toArray(); // [1, 2, 3, 4]

// added line
const resolver = new Resolver();

// Make dns queries concurrently using .map and collect
// the results into an array using toArray
const dnsResults = await Readable.from([
  'nodejs.org',
  'openjsf.org',
  'www.linuxfoundation.org',
]).map(async (domain) => {
  const { address } = await resolver.resolve4(domain, { ttl: true });
  return address;
}, { concurrency: 2 }).toArray();
```

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

**Current Behaviour**

For HTTP/1.1 server, the current "graceful" shutdown procedure when calling [http.Server.close()](https://nodejs.org/api/http.html#serverclosecallback) is as follows:
1. stop accepting new connections (reject new opened TCP connections (this is fine!))
2. let active HTTP requests on already established connections finish (this is also fine!)
3. immediately close idle (keep-alive) connections (THIS IS BAD!)

When the client has currently open HTTP/1.1 keep-alive connections to the Node.js server, those connections are closed by the Node.js server immediately on server shutdown (if they are not actively handling a request). This invokes the race condition of the client sending a new request just as the server decides to close its side of the socket (because the server thinks the connection is idle), yielding a TCP RST for the client.

So, upon calling http.Server.close(), Node.js closes off idle connections _as soon as_ they become idle. If a connection was just serving a HTTP request and entered idle state, it will be closed immediately after entering idle state, even if the client wanted to send a new request right away.

This is especially bad in the case of non-idempotent requests (like POSTs), which would not be retried transparently by any HTTP client and will yield an I/O error (or some form of it) in the client's application.

**Where and why is this a problem**

In an environment, where traffic routing is based on DNS or firewall NAT rules (e.g. Kubernetes with kube-proxy/iptables/netfilter) and a client not having out-of-band information about the server wanting to shut down, this leads to clients still sending new HTTP requests over a connection which the server is about to close.

This is _not_ a problem in "North-South" traffic, where Node.js may be behind a load balancer (like an nginx ingress gateway) which _has_ out-of-band information about the Node.js server wanting to close. With this out-of-band information (i.e. given by watching Kubernetes Endpoints/EndpointSlice objects) a load balancer like nginx ingress can by itself close established connections to Node.js servers which it knows are going to shutdown soon, and not route any more HTTP requests over those connections.

But in "East-West" traffic situations, where the Node.js server is requested by e.g. a Java oder other Node.js or Go client (the nature of the client does not matter) and where the client does _not_ have out-of-band information about the Node.js server wanting to shut down, this will yield above mentioned network errors.

**Behaviour of other server implementations**

Other HTTP server implementations, like Nginx or Envoy proxy, handle this more gracefully by having a "drain period" in which active requests on established connections are still allowed but always automatically including a `Connection: close` header in the response, allowing the client to close the connection without sending new requests over that connection.
In the example of Nginx, this "drain period" is controlled by the [keepalive_min_timeout](https://nginx.org/en/docs/http/ngx_http_core_module.html#keepalive_min_timeout) property. This allows to still keep idle connections alive for new client requests to come in (which will be answered with `Connection: close`) allowing for _truely_ graceful shutdown of the server.

In theory, this "drain period" should be as large as the largest client-side HTTP Keep-Alive/Idle timeout. In the case of Node.js clients (undici) which has a default client-side keep-alive of **4s**, this simply means that the Node.js server should wait at least another **4s** for any possible late request coming in on an idle connection. After this timeout, the server can truely close its side of the connection.

This "drain period" should, of course, be configurable on the http.Server object.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

1. Provide a configurable "drain period" during which after http.Server.close() invocation existing keep-alive idle connections are *not* immediately closed but still allow to wait for incoming requests.

2. Upon http.Server.close(), answer all then incoming requests with `Connection: close`, allowing the client to actively close this connection on its side first

The default for this "drain period" should be 0, effectively leaving the current behaviour of immediately closing idle connections upon http.Server.close() unmodified.

### What alternatives have you considered?

A workaround to this is easily possible by using a custom variable "shutdownInitiated" accessible to the places where signal handling (SIGINT, SIGTERM) takes place and accessible to all places where HTTP requests are handled.

Then:

1. when a signal is caught to shutdown the server, set the `shutdownInitiated` variable to `true` and setTimeout()/sleep for the "drain duration"
2. for each HTTP request handler, check whether `shutdownInitiated` is true and if so, add the `Connection: close` header to the response object
3. after the timer callback for the drain duration fires, call `http.Server.close()` on the Server object

Practically, as a minimal example, this would look like:
```javascript
const http = require('http');
const DRAIN_TIMEOUT = Number(process.env.DRAIN_TIMEOUT) || 5000;
let draining = false;
const server = http.createServer(
    (req, res) => {
        if (draining) {
            res.setHeader('Connection', 'close');
        }
        res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
        res.end('Hello World\n');
    }
);
function gracefulShutdown(sig) {
    console.log(`${sig} signal received. Draining connections...`);
    draining = true;
    setTimeout(() => {
        server.close(() => {
            console.log('Closed remaining connections');
        });
    }, DRAIN_TIMEOUT);
}
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
    gracefulShutdown('SIGTERM')
});
process.on('SIGINT', () => {
    gracefulShutdown('SIGINT')
});
server.listen(3000);
```

An actual http.Server built-in implementation does not actually need to wait for the whole configured drain duration (5s in above example), but can end the drain duration as soon as the TCP connection count drops to zero in the http.Server. This can happen very quickly due to requests on active connections receiving a `Connection: close` during drain duration. Closing the server as soon as there are no opened connections anymore, is fine, upholding the original "contract" of http.Server.close() to immediately stop accepting new connections. In fact, the deployment environment should make sure that e.g. during a rolling update of a fleet of Node.js servers, new TCP connection attempts should never try to reach servers that are in the process of shutting down. The whole problem is therefore reduced to handling idle keep-alive connections that _have already been_ established before the server shutdown process was initiated.

In my opinion, this then implements truely graceful shutdown of the server and its HTTP/1.1 connections, mirroring the behaviour of the Nginx HTTP server (with `keepalive_min_timeout`), resolving any potential race between clients sending new requests over keep-alive connections just as the server is closing them (because the server thinks those are idle now).

**Side note**

I am actually on a venture to analyze and reproduce the graceful shutdown behaviour of all common HTTP servers, including Node.js (and Envoy proxy, nginx, Go, Java/SpringBoot/Tomcat, ...) in the repository: https://github.com/HBTGmbH/httpkeepalive

