body:
### Affected URL(s)

https://nodejs.org/api/readline.html#class-interfaceconstructor

### Description of the problem

The linked document page does not include any information about 'error' events being emitted by a readline interface. As seen in https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/58289, this leads to the conclusion that the only way to see such errors is to attach a handler to the input read stream.

This does not seem to be correct as of Node 16, however. It seems the behavior was changed but the docs were not updated. Using the following example in Node >= 16.0.0:

```js
import {createReadStream} from "node:fs";
import readLine from "node:readline";

let position = 0;
const fakeFs = {
    read: (fd, buffer, offset, len, pos, cb) => {
        if (position < 10) {
            buffer.write("A\n");
            position += 2;
            cb(null, 2, buffer);
        } else {
            cb(new Error("Some read error"));
        }
    },
    close: (fd, cb) => {
        cb();
    },
    open: (name, flags, mode, cb) => {
        cb(undefined, 42);
    },
};

const readStream = createReadStream("foo", { fs: fakeFs });

readStream.on("error", (err) => {
    console.log(`Error on read stream: ${err.message}`);
});

const lineReader = readLine.createInterface({
    input: readStream,
    crlfDelay: Infinity,
});

lineReader.on("line", (line) => {
    console.log(line);
});

lineReader.on("error", (err) => {
    console.log(`Error on line reader: ${err.message}`);
});
```

Outputs:
```
A
A
A
A
A
Error on read stream: Some read error
Error on line reader: Some read error
```

If you omit the error event handler on the line reader interface you get unhandled error event warnings, which is how I noticed this to begin with:

```
A
A
A
A
A
Error on read stream: Some read error
node:events:342
      throw er; // Unhandled 'error' event
      ^

Error: Some read error
    at Object.read (file:///home/sripberger/node-being-stupid/index.js:12:16)
    at ReadStream._read (node:internal/fs/streams:246:6)
    at ReadStream.Readable.read (node:internal/streams/readable:487:10)
    at flow (node:internal/streams/readable:1009:34)
    at resume_ (node:internal/streams/readable:990:3)
    at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues:83:21)
Emitted 'error' event on Interface instance at:
    at ReadStream.onerror (node:readline:248:10)
    at ReadStream.emit (node:events:377:35)
    at emitErrorNT (node:internal/streams/destroy:193:8)
    at emitErrorCloseNT (node:internal/streams/destroy:158:3)
    at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues:83:21)
```

I have verified this same behavior in all the LTS releases from 16 on. I'd say it's more convenient this way, but perhaps the docs should be updated to reflect.

Here's some system other system info in case it is desired:

```
Operating System:
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Platform         : linux
Distro           : Debian GNU/Linux
Release          : 13
Codename         : trixie
Kernel           : 6.6.87.2-microsoft-standard-WSL2
Arch             : x64
```

